<div>
  <h1 class="leading-tight font-bold text-3xl md:text-6xl mb-4 w-full text-gray-800 text-center montserrat">
    A daily email from your <br> favorite websites
  </h1>

  <div class="text-center my-4">
    <%= link_to "Get Started",
      new_user_registration_path,
      class: "btn btn--primary text-white border-4 font-bold py-4 px-6 text-xl"
    %>

    or <%= link_to "Login", new_user_session_path, class: "btn btn--secondary border-4 font-bold py-4 px-6 text-xl" %>

  </div>

  <div class="text-center my-4">
    <p class="text-gray-600">
      Comes as a freemium or <%= link_to "$25/year PRO", pricing_path, class: "text-gray-800 underline font-bold" %>
    </p>
  </div>

</div>
<div>

  <div class="flex justify-around">
    <div class="home-chrome-wrapper my-4 px-4">
      <% unless Rails.env.test? %>
        <%= render "chrome" do %>
          <iframe src="/example-email" class="flex-grow w-full" data-controller="example"></iframe>
        <% end %>
      <% end %>
    </div>
  </div>

</div>

<h1 class="leading-tight font-bold my-4 w-full text-2xl xl:text-4xl text-gray-800 text-center">
  What's Briefcake?
</h1>

<div class="my-4 px-4 flex justify-around">
  <p class="text-gray-600 text-center">
    Perhaps you've got an RSS reader, or folders full of bookmarks, that you last opened FOREVER ago. You're not
    alone. It's actually pretty hard to make checking your favorite websites part of your daily routine.
    <br/><br/>
    That's why we're here with an rss feed reader, that instead of listing new items in an app, sends them in a
    beautifully simple, daily email.
  </p>
</div>
